    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>2008 Campaign's Tone</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dayton Voorhees letter, prompted by Feb 4 article on aides hired by Sen John McCain's presidential campaign whom he has criticized for their work on ads attacking him during 2000 campaign and Sen John Kerry in 2004 campaign, says candidates should resist egocentric, negative politics</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''McCain Embracing Advisers Whose Ads Once Drew His Ire'' (front page, Feb. 4):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''McCain Embracing Advisers Whose Ads Once Drew His Ire'' (front page, Feb. 4):</p>
        <p>Our nation's problems -- terrorism, climate change, entitlements, health care reform -- require thoughtful, long-term solutions. Each party should offer the American people a slate of its best, most innovative and inspiring thinkers rather than have the election process devolve once again into an egocentric, negative politics of personal attack.</p>
        <p>Dayton Voorhees  Corrales, N.M., Feb. 4, 2007</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
